  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Hurricane Iota and asociated emergency response Colombia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">More than a quarter million of people living in Colombia were affected by the tropical storm which turned into category 5 Hurricane Iota hitting the Colombia archipelago of San Andres in November 2020. Rains associated to the tropical storm turned it into a large-scale emergency affecting 25 out of 32 departments in Colombia. SNPS/Caritas Colombiana is leading a coordinated response which will include a response in Choco Department where this emergency comes on to top of the ongoing armed conflict, as well as Cartagena where 70% of the city had been flooded. They are aiming to support 12.000 people over 9 months, prioritised groups include children, pregnant women and women with small children, older adults and people with disabilities (this will depend on level of funds raised). Components include WASH (hygiene kits, access to clean water) and COVID prevention, shelter, NFI and food among others.  COVID prevention measures and information sharing will also be important components.</narrative>
  </description>
